## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## doc-align
##
## Detects mismatches between documentation (README, docs/*.md,
## CLAUDE.md, bundled skills, optionally Go code comments) and the
## actual current state of the code, then fixes the DOCUMENTATION
## (never the code) and auto-commits on convergence.
##
## Workflow shape mirrors branch_improve_loop:
##   - Alternating Claude (claude_code/opus) and GPT (claw/gpt-5.5)
##     reviewers via round_robin router
##   - Deterministic `streak_check` (compute) requiring two
##     consecutive cross-family approvals
##   - `prepare_commit` agent + `commit_changes` shell tool finalize
##
## Specificity vs branch_improve_loop:
##   - A deterministic upstream `scan_docs` tool node enumerates the
##     doc footprint ONCE (python3 + sha1) so the audit set is
##     IMMUTABLE — agents cannot truncate it (anti-Goodhart, see
##     `docs/workflow_authoring_pitfalls.md`).
##   - The verdict schema carries `audited_pairs` (doc_path::code_anchor
##     tuples verified this iteration) and `escalate_to_human` (set
##     when a blocker has `is_code_bug=true`).
##   - The fix schema carries `modified_doc_files` and
##     `code_files_touched`; the latter MUST be empty — non-empty is
##     a workflow contract violation that the next reviewer flags
##     as a high-confidence blocker.
##
## Inviolable rules (enforced by skills + prompts):
##   1. Docs follow code; code does NOT follow docs.
##   2. Fixer writeable set: `.md` files in scope + Go code comments
##      when `go_comment_globs` is non-empty.
##   3. The audit footprint is determined by the scanner tool, not
##      by agents.
##   4. Escape valve: when the doc is correct and the code is wrong,
##      set `is_code_bug=true` and call `ask_user` — never silently
##      rewrite a correct doc to match buggy code.
##
## Skills shipped: doc-align (playbook), doc-mismatch-taxonomy (10-
## value enum), doc-scope-enumeration (scanner contract),
## anti-facade-fix-rules (substantive fix discipline),
## doc-verification-checklist (judge STEP-0 preamble).
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

vars:
  workspace_dir: string = "${PROJECT_DIR}"

  ## Doc footprint scope (comma-separated globs). The scan_docs tool
  ## node enumerates files matching these globs once, at run start.
  ## Hidden / vendored dirs (.iterion, .works, .claude, vendor,
  ## node_modules, .git, dist, build, out) are excluded
  ## unconditionally inside the scanner.
  doc_globs: string = "README.md,CLAUDE.md,docs/**/*.md,**/CLAUDE.md,examples/*/skills/*.md"

  ## Go code comment scope (comma-separated globs). Empty (default)
  ## means: do NOT audit Go function/package comments — speeds up
  ## first runs. When non-empty, reviewers also check `//` and
  ## `/* */` comments inside matching files; fixers may edit those
  ## comments (but never the code statements around them).
  go_comment_globs: string = ""

  ## Where reviewers MAY grep / read to verify doc claims. They
  ## do not modify these files — they only consult them as ground
  ## truth for the doc audit.
  code_scope_globs: string = "pkg/**/*.go,cmd/**/*.go,internal/**/*.go"

  ## Optional free-text notes pinning the reviewers' attention to a
  ## recent area of churn or a known issue. Empty by default.
  scope_notes: string = ""

  ## Loop bounds. review_loop counts reviewer iterations;
  ## recovery_loop counts fixer iterations. Total fix attempts
  ## across both families share recovery_loop.
  max_review_iterations: int = 15
  max_recovery_iterations: int = 20


## ─── Prompts ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

prompt review_system:
  You are a rigorous documentation reviewer for the `doc-align`
  workflow. Your job is to detect mismatches between project
  documentation and the actual current state of the code, and to
  produce a structured verdict.

  LOAD YOUR SKILLS FIRST. The workflow ships five skills under
  `.claude/skills/` describing the discipline you MUST follow:
    - `doc-align.md` — operating playbook, the why and the
      inviolable rules
    - `doc-mismatch-taxonomy.md` — the 10 mismatch_kind enum
      values you must use to tag every blocker
    - `doc-scope-enumeration.md` — the immutable scan_docs
      footprint contract
    - `doc-verification-checklist.md` — the STEP-0 preamble you
      MUST run before voting approved=true
    - `anti-facade-fix-rules.md` — what a façade fix looks like
      (used to detect façades in prior iterations)

  Read them before reasoning. Then run STEP 0 through STEP 6 of
  `doc-verification-checklist.md` literally. Skipping steps
  defeats the workflow's false-positive defenses.

  THE INVIOLABLE RULES (restated for emphasis):
   1. Docs follow code; code does NOT follow docs. You correct
      documentation to match the code, not the other way around.
   2. The audit footprint is `input.doc_files[]` from `scan_docs`.
      It is immutable. You cannot drop files; if you cannot verify
      a file, raise a coverage gap, do not silently skip.
   3. If a doc is correct and the code is wrong, set
      `is_code_bug=true` on the blocker and call `ask_user`. Do
      NOT raise it as a fixable mismatch — the bot does not edit
      code.
   4. Pre-iteration check: examine `outputs.fix_claude.code_files_touched`
      and `outputs.fix_gpt.code_files_touched` from the previous
      fix iteration. Both MUST be `[]`. If either is non-empty,
      raise an automatic blocker (`severity: high`,
      `confidence: high`) describing the contract violation. This
      is the G4 gate from the bot's design.

  PATH-OF-LEAST-RESISTANCE WARNING:
   You will be tempted to focus on docs colocated with code that
   has been recently changed. Resist. Audit every file in
   `input.doc_files[]` over the course of the loop. Coverage of
   the full footprint is the success criterion, not coverage of
   the obvious surfaces.

  HUMAN ESCALATION:
   When you hit genuine ambiguity (doc and code disagree and you
   cannot tell which is wrong from the code alone, or a doc claim
   depends on intent you cannot infer), call `ask_user` with a
   precise question. The run will pause, the operator will answer,
   and you will be re-invoked with the answer in context. Use this
   sparingly — for ordinary judgment calls, decide yourself and
   lower `confidence` if uncertain.

prompt review_user_claude:
  Audit the documentation in {{vars.workspace_dir}} against the
  actual code state.

  Doc footprint (immutable — the complete audit set):
  {{input.doc_files}}

  Doc count: {{input.doc_count}}
  Footprint hash: {{input.footprint_hash}}
  Scope globs: {{input.scope_globs}}

  Code scope for verification (read-only consult):
  {{vars.code_scope_globs}}

  Go comment scope (empty = skip Go comments):
  {{vars.go_comment_globs}}

  Scope notes (operator's attention pin):
  {{vars.scope_notes}}

  Iteration: {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}

  Previous reviewer's verdict (other family, immediately prior
  iteration — empty on first iteration):
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Cumulative audited pairs across all prior iterations (use to
  prioritise uncovered files):
  {{input.previous_audited_pairs}}

  Items already pushed back by the fixer (do NOT re-flag without
  fresh evidence):
  {{input.prior_pushback}}

  Pushback justification:
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  Previous fix iteration's `code_files_touched` (MUST be empty —
  non-empty = automatic contract violation blocker):
  {{outputs.fix_claude.code_files_touched}} / {{outputs.fix_gpt.code_files_touched}}

  Now run STEP 0 through STEP 6 of `doc-verification-checklist.md`
  and emit a verdict with these fields:
    - approved: bool (true only when coverage AND no blockers)
    - family: "claude"
    - blockers: array of structured mismatch objects (see
      `doc-mismatch-taxonomy.md` for the 10 mismatch_kind enum
      values and the required fields: doc_path, doc_line_start,
      doc_line_end, doc_excerpt, code_anchor, code_state,
      mismatch_kind, severity, suggested_fix, is_code_bug)
    - fix_plan: concrete instruction set for the fixer (short)
    - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
    - audited_pairs: list of "doc_path::code_anchor" strings you
      ACTUALLY verified this iteration
    - escalate_to_human: true if ANY blocker has is_code_bug=true

prompt review_user_gpt:
  Audit the documentation in {{vars.workspace_dir}} against the
  actual code state.

  Doc footprint (immutable — the complete audit set):
  {{input.doc_files}}

  Doc count: {{input.doc_count}}
  Footprint hash: {{input.footprint_hash}}
  Scope globs: {{input.scope_globs}}

  Code scope for verification (read-only consult):
  {{vars.code_scope_globs}}

  Go comment scope (empty = skip Go comments):
  {{vars.go_comment_globs}}

  Scope notes (operator's attention pin):
  {{vars.scope_notes}}

  Iteration: {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}

  Previous reviewer's verdict (other family, immediately prior
  iteration — empty on first iteration):
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Cumulative audited pairs across all prior iterations:
  {{input.previous_audited_pairs}}

  Items already pushed back by the fixer:
  {{input.prior_pushback}}

  Pushback justification:
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  Previous fix iteration's `code_files_touched` (MUST be empty):
  {{outputs.fix_claude.code_files_touched}} / {{outputs.fix_gpt.code_files_touched}}

  Now run STEP 0 through STEP 6 of `doc-verification-checklist.md`
  and emit a verdict with these fields:
    - approved: bool
    - family: "gpt"
    - blockers: array of structured mismatch objects (see
      `doc-mismatch-taxonomy.md`)
    - fix_plan: short concrete instruction set for the fixer
    - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
    - audited_pairs: list of "doc_path::code_anchor" you verified
    - escalate_to_human: true if any blocker has is_code_bug=true

prompt fix_system:
  You are the fixer for the `doc-align` workflow. You apply
  corrections to DOCUMENTATION files based on blockers a reviewer
  has identified.

  LOAD YOUR SKILLS FIRST. Especially:
    - `anti-facade-fix-rules.md` — the discipline rules. A fix
      where your `summary` does not cite the tool invocation
      (read_file / grep) that verified the cited `code_anchor`
      is a façade, and the next reviewer will reject it.
    - `doc-mismatch-taxonomy.md` — the kind / severity meanings.
    - `doc-scope-enumeration.md` — what you may and may not
      write to.

  HARD CONSTRAINTS:
   1. Writeable extensions: `.md` only, AND (when go_comment_globs
      is non-empty) Go code comments inside files matching that
      scope. You may NEVER write to a `.go` statement, expression,
      or declaration body.
   2. `fix_output.code_files_touched[]` MUST be empty in your
      output. The next reviewer will flag non-empty as a workflow
      contract violation (high-confidence blocker).
   3. `fix_output.modified_doc_files[]` MUST be a subset of
      `input.doc_files` (the scanner footprint). You cannot
      introduce new doc files; you cannot edit docs outside scope.
   4. For each fix you apply, your `summary` MUST contain the
      tool invocation (`read_file` or `grep`) you used to verify
      the current code state at the cited `code_anchor`. Without
      that evidence the fix is a façade.

  ESCAPE VALVE:
   If a blocker has `is_code_bug=true`, do NOT attempt to fix it.
   Add it to `pushback` with a justification explaining that the
   doc appears correct and the code is the problem. Call
   `ask_user` to surface the question to the operator if you
   need confirmation.

  PUSHBACK:
   You may refuse a blocker by adding its exact description to
   `pushback[]` with a clear justification in
   `pushback_justification`. Use this for false positives or
   stylistic findings the reviewer should not have raised.
   Pushback is the supported "this is not a real mismatch"
   channel; silent skip is not.

prompt fix_user:
  Apply doc-only fixes for these blockers in
  {{vars.workspace_dir}}.

  Doc footprint (your writeable set, plus Go code comments inside
  go_comment_globs when non-empty):
  {{vars.doc_globs}}

  Go comment scope (empty = no Go comments may be edited):
  {{vars.go_comment_globs}}

  Blockers to address:
  {{input.blockers}}

  Fix plan from the reviewer:
  {{input.fix_plan}}

  For EACH blocker:
   1. Read the code at the cited `code_anchor` to verify the
      current state. Paste the tool invocation and an excerpt
      into your `summary`.
   2. If the blocker is genuine and is_code_bug is false: apply
      the fix to the doc. Run the negative-space check
      (`git grep` for stale cross-references to whatever you
      removed) and fix those too in the same pass.
   3. If `is_code_bug=true`: do NOT fix. Push back with a
      justification.
   4. If the blocker is a false positive: push back with
      justification.

  Output fields:
   - applied: true if at least one fix landed
   - summary: list of fixes with their tool-invocation evidence
     (see `anti-facade-fix-rules.md` for the expected shape)
   - modified_doc_files: exact list of repo-relative paths you
     wrote to (must be subset of input.doc_files)
   - code_files_touched: MUST be []
   - pushback: items refused
   - pushback_justification: explanation


## ─── Prompts : Commit ──────────────────────────────────────────

prompt prepare_commit_system:
  Your job is to pick the EXACT set of doc files that should be
  committed to capture the alignment fixes applied during this
  run, and produce a semantic commit message. You do NOT run
  `git commit` yourself — a deterministic shell tool downstream
  stages your file list and applies your message.

  Procedure (in order):
   1. Run `git status` and `git diff HEAD` (read-only) to
      enumerate working-tree changes.
   2. Cross-reference with the original scanner footprint
      (visible in your conversation history if you scroll back,
      or rerun the equivalent `find`). The commit set must be a
      subset of that footprint, plus any Go file whose comments
      were edited (no Go file should be on the list with code
      changes — verify by running `git diff HEAD -- <file>` and
      confirming only comment lines changed).
   3. EXCLUDE any non-doc file. EXCLUDE any LLM scratch
      (`notes.md`, `plan.txt`, etc.) the fixer accidentally
      created. EXCLUDE editor scratch and build artefacts.
   4. Build the structured output:
       - type: "docs" (default) or "fix" (only when you fixed a
         demonstrably misleading code COMMENT that would have led
         readers astray)
       - scope: typical package/area name, lowercase
       - subject: imperative present, ≤ 72 chars, no trailing
         period (e.g. "align CLI examples with current flags")
       - full_message: type(scope): subject — plus an optional
         body summarising what was aligned
       - files: exact list of repo-relative paths to stage
       - committed: false (the tool will set this on its own
         output)

prompt prepare_commit_user:
  Pick the files and produce the semantic commit name for the
  doc alignment fixes applied during this doc-align run.

  Workspace: {{vars.workspace_dir}}


## ─── Schemas ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## scan_output is the immutable doc footprint emitted by the
## upstream scan_docs tool node. It anchors the audit set for the
## entire run.
schema scan_output:
  doc_files: string[]
  doc_count: int
  footprint_hash: string
  scope_globs: string[]

## review_input: what each reviewer sees on entry. doc_files /
## doc_count / footprint_hash / scope_globs come from scan_docs
## (relayed through the alt router). previous_audited_pairs
## accumulates audit coverage across all prior iterations (both
## families).
schema review_input:
  doc_files: string[]
  doc_count: int
  footprint_hash: string
  scope_globs: string[]
  prior_pushback: string[]
  prior_pushback_justification: string
  previous_audited_pairs: string[]

## verdict_output: a reviewer's structured judgment. `blockers` is
## JSON to allow nested mismatch objects (the DSL schema parser
## only supports primitive types and string[], so structured
## arrays go through json). The per-blocker fields are described
## in skills/doc-mismatch-taxonomy.md and enforced at the prompt
## level.
##
## family is enum-locked: a hallucinated value would otherwise
## bypass both family-aware fix routes and silently terminate the
## workflow. The enum forces structured-output validation to
## reject the verdict, triggering parse_fallback retry.
schema verdict_output:
  approved: bool
  family: string [enum: "claude", "gpt"]
  blockers: json
  fix_plan: string
  confidence: string [enum: "low", "medium", "high"]
  audited_pairs: string[]
  escalate_to_human: bool

## streak_state: passthrough from the current verdict + the
## deterministic cross-family streak detection. Mirrors the
## pattern in whole_improve_loop.bot. cumulative_audited_pairs
## accumulates monotonically via
## `unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_audited_pairs,
## input.audited_pairs))`.
schema streak_state:
  stop: bool
  approved: bool
  family: string
  blockers: json
  fix_plan: string
  cumulative_audited_pairs: string[]

## fix_input: blockers + plan handed to the same-family fixer.
schema fix_input:
  blockers: json
  fix_plan: string

## fix_output: the fixer's report. code_files_touched MUST be
## empty — non-empty is a contract violation flagged by the next
## reviewer (G4 gate).
schema fix_output:
  applied: bool
  summary: string
  modified_doc_files: string[]
  code_files_touched: string[]
  pushback: string[]
  pushback_justification: string

## Commit-phase schemas, mirroring branch_improve_loop.
## type enum is narrower here — only `docs` and `fix` make sense
## for a docs-only bot (`fix` reserved for misleading Go-comment
## corrections).
schema commit_output:
  type: string [enum: "docs", "fix"]
  scope: string
  subject: string
  full_message: string
  files: string[]
  committed: bool

schema commit_tool_input:
  full_message: string
  files: string[]
  workspace_dir: string

schema commit_result:
  success: bool
  output: string


## ─── Nodes ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## scan_docs is the deterministic upstream scanner. It runs ONCE
## per workflow run (before the review loop opens) and emits the
## immutable doc footprint that anchors the entire run.
##
## Implementation: python3 -c "..." with env vars WS and GLOBS
## injected from iterion vars at template-resolution time. Python
## handles ** globs natively (`glob.glob(recursive=True)`) and the
## EXCLUDE set unconditionally drops hidden / vendored / runtime
## directories (.iterion, .works, .claude, vendor, node_modules,
## .git, dist, build, out) so they cannot leak into the audit
## footprint even if a permissive glob is configured.
##
## Output is JSON on stdout; the iterion tool-node executor parses
## it into the scan_output schema fields automatically.
##
## Raw-string (backtick) form chosen because the python snippet
## contains many quote characters that would drown in `\"` escapes
## in the standard "..." string form.
tool scan_docs:
  command: `WS={{vars.workspace_dir}} GLOBS={{vars.doc_globs}} python3 -c "
import os, json, glob, hashlib
ws = os.environ['WS']
globs = [g.strip() for g in os.environ['GLOBS'].split(',') if g.strip()]
os.chdir(ws)
EXCLUDE = {'.iterion', '.works', '.claude', 'vendor', 'node_modules', '.git', 'dist', 'build', 'out'}
files = sorted({f for g in globs for f in glob.glob(g, recursive=True) if os.path.isfile(f) and not any(p in EXCLUDE for p in f.split(os.sep))})
h = hashlib.sha1(chr(10).join(files).encode()).hexdigest()
print(json.dumps({'doc_files': files, 'doc_count': len(files), 'footprint_hash': h, 'scope_globs': globs}))
"`
  output: scan_output

router alt:
  mode: round_robin

judge reviewer_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "claude-opus-4-7"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-max}"
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_claude
  session: fresh
  interaction: human

judge reviewer_gpt:
  ## Explicit backend pin: openai/gpt-5.5 only runs on claw.
  ## Without it the auto-resolver picks claude_code, which doesn't
  ## know the model id, and the agent returns a meta-error.
  backend: "claw"
  model: "openai/gpt-5.5"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_EFFORT_GPT:-high}"
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_gpt
  session: fresh
  ## claw builtin tools use snake_case names. Read-only set: the
  ## reviewer NEVER writes.
  tools: [bash, read_file, glob, grep]
  tool_max_steps: 40
  interaction: human

## Deterministic streak detector. Two consecutive cross-family
## approvals → stop. Soft-approval (low-confidence rejection) is
## passed through as approved for routing (alternation continues
## without invoking the fixer) but does NOT count toward the stop
## streak.
compute streak_check:
  output: streak_state
  expr:
    stop: "input.approved && loop.review_loop.previous_output.approved && input.family != loop.review_loop.previous_output.family"
    approved: "input.approved || input.confidence == 'low'"
    family: "input.family"
    blockers: "input.blockers"
    fix_plan: "input.fix_plan"
    cumulative_audited_pairs: "unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_audited_pairs, input.audited_pairs))"

agent fix_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "claude-opus-4-7"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-max}"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  interaction: human

agent fix_gpt:
  backend: "claw"
  model: "openai/gpt-5.5"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_EFFORT_GPT:-high}"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  ## claw needs read+write tools for fixers to actually edit docs.
  tools: [bash, read_file, write_file, file_edit, glob, grep]
  tool_max_steps: 40
  interaction: human


## ─── Nodes : Commit ─────────────────────────────────────────────

agent prepare_commit:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "claude-opus-4-7"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-max}"
  output: commit_output
  system: prepare_commit_system
  user: prepare_commit_user
  session: fresh
  readonly: true

## commit_changes: deterministic shell tool. Stages exactly the
## file list prepare_commit chose; commits with the semantic
## message. The `diff --cached --quiet` guard skips the commit
## if `git add` resolved to nothing (e.g. all listed files were
## clean by the time we reached this node).
tool commit_changes:
  command: "git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} add -- {{input.files}} && (git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} diff --cached --quiet || git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} commit -m {{input.full_message}})"
  input: commit_tool_input
  output: commit_result


## ─── Workflow ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

workflow doc_align:
  entry: scan_docs

  budget:
    max_parallel_branches: 1
    max_duration: "4h"
    max_cost_usd: 120

  compaction:
    threshold: 0.9
    preserve_recent: 8

  ## scan_docs runs ONCE upstream of the review loop. Its output
  ## (doc_files, doc_count, footprint_hash, scope_globs) is
  ## relayed to every reviewer iteration via the alt -> reviewer_*
  ## edges below. Because outputs.scan_docs.* is referenced
  ## (not loop.scan_docs), the value resolved on every reviewer
  ## invocation is the single, immutable scanner output from the
  ## first iteration.
  scan_docs -> alt

  ## Round-robin alternates: 1st pass → claude, 2nd → gpt, repeat.
  ## Each reviewer receives:
  ##   - the immutable scanner footprint (doc_files / doc_count /
  ##     footprint_hash / scope_globs)
  ##   - the OTHER family's most recent fixer pushback
  ##   - the cumulative audited pairs from prior iterations
  alt -> reviewer_claude with {
    doc_files: "{{outputs.scan_docs.doc_files}}",
    doc_count: "{{outputs.scan_docs.doc_count}}",
    footprint_hash: "{{outputs.scan_docs.footprint_hash}}",
    scope_globs: "{{outputs.scan_docs.scope_globs}}",
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback_justification}}",
    previous_audited_pairs: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_audited_pairs}}"
  }
  alt -> reviewer_gpt with {
    doc_files: "{{outputs.scan_docs.doc_files}}",
    doc_count: "{{outputs.scan_docs.doc_count}}",
    footprint_hash: "{{outputs.scan_docs.footprint_hash}}",
    scope_globs: "{{outputs.scan_docs.scope_globs}}",
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback_justification}}",
    previous_audited_pairs: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_audited_pairs}}"
  }

  ## reviewer → streak_check carries the review_loop counter so
  ## `loop.review_loop.previous_output` snapshots the prior
  ## verdict for the next iteration. Bounded at 15 iterations
  ## per loop-counter — exhaustion falls through to the
  ## unconditional reviewer → done edges below.
  reviewer_claude -> streak_check as review_loop(15) with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.confidence}}",
    audited_pairs: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.audited_pairs}}"
  }
  reviewer_gpt -> streak_check as review_loop(15) with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.confidence}}",
    audited_pairs: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.audited_pairs}}"
  }

  ## Stop on cross-family double approval — route to commit phase.
  streak_check -> prepare_commit when stop

  prepare_commit -> commit_changes with {
    full_message: "{{outputs.prepare_commit.full_message}}",
    files: "{{outputs.prepare_commit.files}}",
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}"
  }

  commit_changes -> done

  ## Soft-approval (no streak yet, or low-confidence rejection):
  ## keep alternating without invoking the fixer. This edge
  ## does NOT carry review_loop so the loop counter is incremented
  ## once per cycle on the reviewer→streak_check edges above.
  streak_check -> alt when "approved"

  ## Medium/high-confidence rejection with concrete blockers:
  ## route to the SAME-family fixer so it inherits the reviewer's
  ## session (one session per iteration per family). The
  ## length(blockers) > 0 guard avoids invoking the fixer on
  ## coverage-only rejections (the unconditional alt fallthrough
  ## handles those).
  ##
  ## Edge order matters: iterion evaluates conditional edges top-
  ## down, first match wins. Family-specific fixers listed before
  ## the unconditional fallthroughs.
  streak_check -> fix_claude when "!approved && family == 'claude' && length(blockers) > 0" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude._session_id}}"
  }
  streak_check -> fix_gpt when "!approved && family == 'gpt' && length(blockers) > 0" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt._session_id}}"
  }

  ## Recovery cycle uses a separate loop name. Both fixers share
  ## the loop counter — total fix attempts capped at 20.
  fix_claude -> alt as recovery_loop(20)
  fix_gpt    -> alt as recovery_loop(20)

  ## Loop-exhaustion fallthroughs.
  reviewer_claude -> done
  reviewer_gpt    -> done
  fix_claude      -> done
  fix_gpt         -> done
  ## streak_check's catch-all routes back to alt (not done) so an
  ## unmatched conditional state (e.g. a hallucinated family that
  ## escaped the enum) keeps the loop cycling rather than silently
  ## terminating. The bounded review_loop counter still guarantees
  ## exit via the reviewer→done fallthroughs.
  streak_check    -> alt
